Q21: Things were quite hard to find because it seemed like documents had overlapping information so it was often confusing. It's possible that there were too many separate documents and that maybe having one with multiple tabs or one master folder with all the information/sub-folders would have been more clear/helpful. An alternative suggestion would be to have one document with all the links to relevant folders/documents included. This is what our lab ended up creating so that there was one place where we could quickly access all the necessary information without having to sort through multiple places. The information regarding data input was also very confusing - particularly the inclusion and exclusion criteria - there was no clear definition regarding what to base these decisions on (e.g. if a baby fussed out would you exclude the entire baby or just the trials that they were fussy for). Another example includes the variable explanations page which was useful but was missing quite a bit of information which we had to dig through other documents to find.
Q29: Provided more information regarding data input, specifically details of the participant vs. trial exclusion criteria and how to indicate this. There were different criterion for each of the data documents which was a little confusing.

Q21: I actually don't find OSF that intuitive an interface. Not really a suggestion for improvement - I don't know that using the drive alone or github would be any better. Q23: We ran in to difficulty marking the end of trials. We do our coding (HPP) offline by first marking the video files for beginning and end of trial as beginning of sound presentation to end of sound presentation.
